tweet: The Fed's balance sheet has grown by $3.4 trillion since March 2020. The deficit (Feb-Jan 20 vs 21) is $2.4 trillion higher. And yet core inflation ticks down to 1.3%. Sure it will go up, but it makes you wonder about just how strong the deflationary forces are in this world.

tweet: Part of the Fed's communications problem is how complex and confusing its message is: it has to stanch market expectations that it will hike sooner than expected (be dovish) and at the same time tell market it's not going to act preemptively to keep a lid on rates (be hawkish).

name: Steve Liesman
tweet: I think the selloff today comes down to this: the market  wants the fed to have its back on rising yields and and Fed is not offering any assurances. Powell has been clear he doesn't want to intervene at these levels. My reporting suggests others on FOMC support this position.

tweet: Which is to say, I don’t see a need for any additional regulation. People should  be free to stick it to the man. I just don’t find it  a very compelling or enduring investment thesis.

name: Steve Liesman
tweet: But I think the fundamental economic interests of the buyers assert themselves quickly so such coordination is short lived. And  company fundamentals of the particular stock will tend to win out over all that in the long run.

name: Steve Liesman
tweet: Differing gains and losses among investors would tend to separate the group over even short horizons. What does endure I think is the marriage of widespread access to options and calls and message boards that can magnify the effect of coordinated buying and selling for a time.
